===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|bleden}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|blēdan||to bleed}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*blōþijaną||to bleed}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*blōþą||blood}}. Cognate with Scots {{m|sco|blede}}, {{m|sco|bleid||to bleed}}, West Frisian {{term|bliede||to bleed|lang=fy}}, Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|bläide||to bleed}}, Dutch {{term|bloeden||to bleed|lang=nl}}, Low German {{term|blöden||to bleed|lang=nds}}, German {{term|bluten||to bleed|lang=de}}, Danish {{term|bløde||to bleed|lang=da}}, Swedish {{term|blöda||to bleed|lang=sv}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈbliːd/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iːd|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|bleeds|bleeding|bled}}

# {{context|intransitive|of an animal|lang=en}} To [[lose]] [[blood]] through an [[injured]] [[blood vessel]].
#: ''If her nose '''bleeds''' try to use ice.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[let]] or [[draw]] [[blood]] from.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[take]] large amounts of [[money]] from.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To steadily lose (something vital).
#: ''The company was '''bleeding''' talent.''
# {{context|intransitive|of an ink or dye|lang=en}} To [[spread]] from the intended location and [[stain]] the surrounding [[cloth]] or [[paper]].
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[remove]] [[air]] bubbles from a [[pipe]] containing [[fluid]]s.
# {{context|obsolete|transitive|lang=en}} To bleed on; to make bloody.
#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtArthr1|VIII}}:
#*: And so Sir Trystrames '''bledde''' bothe the over-shete and the neyther-shete, and the pylowes and the hede-shete
# {{context|intransitive|copulative|lang=en}} To show one's group loyalty by showing (its associated color) in one's blood.
#: ''He was a devoted Vikings fan: he '''bled''' purple.''
# To lose sap, gum, or juice.
#: ''A tree or a vine '''bleeds''' when tapped or wounded.''
# To issue forth, or drop, like blood from an incision.
#* Alexander Pope
#*: For me the balm shall '''bleed'''.
# {{context|phonology|transitive|of a phonological rule|lang=en}} To destroy the environment where another phonological rule would have applied.
#: ''Labialization '''bleeds''' palatalization.''

